# Forge project conventions — {{.Name}}

> **This file is forge-managed.** It is written once by `{{.CLI}} new` (and is not regenerated by `{{.CLI}} generate`). Do not hand-edit — changes will be lost if you re-scaffold. Put project-specific notes in the top-level `reliant.md` instead.

This is a **Forge** project — a Connect RPC development framework purpose-built for LLM-driven development. Everything in the stack communicates over Connect RPC interfaces generated from `proto/` files, which makes every boundary mockable, swappable, and spec-driven.

## Philosophy

- **Proto-first.** The contract lives in `proto/`. Go handlers, clients, and DTOs under `gen/` are all derived from it. If you want to change a message or RPC, change the proto and regenerate — never hand-edit `gen/`.
- **Everything is Connect RPC.** Services talk to each other (and to frontends) through the same interface pattern. There are no side-channel APIs.
- **Internal boundaries use Go interfaces.** For components that can't be expressed in proto (channels, complex types, factories), `{{.CLI}} package new <name>` creates an `internal/<name>/contract.go` with an interface contract, and codegen produces mocks and middleware from it.
- **Mockable by default.** Because every boundary — Connect or Go-interface — has generated mocks, tests can swap real implementations without rewiring anything.
- **Convention over configuration.** `{{.CLI}} new`, `{{.CLI}} add`, `{{.CLI}} package`, and the `Taskfile.yml` encode the project layout. Follow them and the CLI keeps working. Fight them and you're on your own.
- **LLM-optimized.** File layout, naming, and scaffolding are chosen so an agent can find things by pattern. Don't "cleverly" reorganize — you'll break the conventions other agents rely on.

## Rules

- **Never hand-edit anything under `gen/`.** It's overwritten on every `{{.CLI}} generate`. Fix the `.proto` instead.
- **`gen/` is not committed.** Only `gen/go.mod` and `gen/go.sum` are tracked. Fresh clones must run `{{.CLI}} generate` before `{{.CLI}} run` or `{{.CLI}} test`.
- **Run `{{.CLI}} generate` after any proto change.** Stale generated code is the #1 source of mysterious compile errors.
- **Use `{{.CLI}} test`, not raw `go test`.** The CLI sets the right build tags (`integration`) that bare `go test` would skip.
- **Use `{{.CLI}} debug`, not raw `dlv`.** The CLI manages session state in `.forge/debug-session.json` so subsequent commands reconnect to the same session. Step commands are **`stepin`** / **`stepout`** (no hyphens).
- **All `{{.CLI}} db migrate ...` commands require `--dsn`.** Set `DATABASE_URL` once in your shell: `export DATABASE_URL="postgres://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/{{.Name}}?sslmode=disable"`.
- **Migrations are append-only history.** Once merged, never edit a migration — write a new one.
- **Secrets never live in the repo.** Not in KCL, not in code, not in comments. Use cluster-level secret management.
- **`{{.CLI}} deploy` takes the environment as a positional arg**, not `--env`. Production deploys require explicitly typing `prod`.
- **`{{.CLI}} package new` creates internal Go packages, not Docker images.** Docker image builds live under `{{.CLI}} build --docker`.

## Skills — use these playbooks

When a task matches one of the situations below, open the linked skill and follow it. They encode the project's opinionated workflows and the non-obvious gotchas. Every command referenced in a skill is verified against the CLI by a test in `internal/generator/`.

Ordered by workflow:

| Situation | Skill |
| --- | --- |
| Adding a new service or frontend | `.reliant/skills/forge/add/SKILL.md` |
| Creating an internal Go package with an interface contract | `.reliant/skills/forge/package/SKILL.md` |
| Regenerating code from `.proto` files | `.reliant/skills/forge/generate/SKILL.md` |
| Running the dev stack with hot reload | `.reliant/skills/forge/run/SKILL.md` |
| Running unit + integration tests | `.reliant/skills/forge/test/SKILL.md` |
| Running end-to-end tests against a running stack | `.reliant/skills/forge/e2e-test/SKILL.md` |
| Debugging a running service with Delve or CDP | `.reliant/skills/forge/debug/SKILL.md` |
| Building production or debug binaries, or Docker images | `.reliant/skills/forge/build/SKILL.md` |
| Running linters across Go, proto, and frontend | `.reliant/skills/forge/lint/SKILL.md` |
| Database migrations, introspection, proto-db sync | `.reliant/skills/forge/db/SKILL.md` |
| Deploying to k3d, staging, or prod via KCL | `.reliant/skills/forge/deploy/SKILL.md` |

Browse the full set in `.reliant/skills/` — each skill has YAML frontmatter with a `when_to_use` list you can pattern-match against the current task.

## MCP servers

Project-level MCP servers are configured in `.mcp.json`. The defaults are:

- **`chrome-devtools`** — drive a real browser for frontend debugging, E2E verification, and Chrome DevTools Protocol inspection.
- **`reliant-docs`** — search Reliant and Forge documentation inline.

A `.mcp.json.example` in the project root lists additional MCPs you can opt into (e.g., postgres). Copy entries from the example file into `.mcp.json` to enable them.